	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Louisville Ky</placeName> <date>October 16th 1851</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
				<p>Trusting that this letter will reach you in time for the <date>November</date><lb/> Occident&#44; I&#39;ll make you acquainted with the proceedings of a general<lb/> meeting of this congregation&#44; held last night.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In short&#44; all and every one of the old officers were unani&#44;<lb/>mously re&#45;elected.  The same was the case with me.  A more<lb/> quiet&#44; friendly&#44; untied and orderly meeting was never witnessed<lb/> After the adjournment the President <persName>M. Strau<del>s</del>s</persName>&#44; <persName>E. Lieber&#44;<lb/>man</persName>&#44; <persName>Abm Gerstly</persName>&#44; <persName>L. Lowensahn</persName>&#44; <persName>S. Ullman</persName>&#44; <persName>T. Tessil</persName>&#44; <persName>L. Silberman</persName> and others.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I feel happy indeed&#44; not because I am re&#45;elected&#44; but<lb/> for the friendly spirit&#44; for the harmony and union which exists<lb/> at present in this congregation&#8212;and I may flatter myself that<lb/> my own humble exertions have added&#44; the least&#44; something to<lb/> this happy state of congregational affairs.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">All the officers&#44; without exception are well worthy our<lb/> meriting the confidence&#44; the respect and esteem <del>of</del> they acquired.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Please take notice of these few lines&#44; without taking notice<lb/> of my bad english.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I shall soon seek for an opportunity to let you hear<lb/> from me again</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">truly and sincerely</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)"><persName role="author">BH. Gotthelf</persName></p>
				<p>P.S. The Hebrew Benevolent Ladys Society No I.</p>
				<p>held their meeting the day previous and re&#45;elected<lb/> all their officers&#8212;<persName>Mrs B. Marks</persName> President.  I took several times occasion<lb/> to report to you their harmony and their many benevolent and charitable<lb/> acts&#44; but as yet you have omitted to mention anything about it.</p>
		</body>
